SIMPLE: show
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Show
<hw>Show</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Showed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Shown</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Showed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr.
& vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Showing</conjf>. <altsp>It is sometimes written
<asp>shew</asp>, <asp>shewed</asp>, <asp>shewn</asp>,
<asp>shewing</asp>.</altsp>]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>schowen</ets>,
<ets>shewen</ets>, <ets>schewen</ets>, <ets>shawen</ets>, AS.
<ets>sce⟦aacute⟧wian</ets>, to look, see, view; akin to OS.
<ets>scaw<?/n</ets>, OFries. <ets>skawia</ets>, D. <ets>schouwen</ets>,
OHG. <ets>scouw<?/n</ets>, G. <ets>schauen</ets>, Dan. <ets>skue</ets>,
Sw. <ets>sk<?/da</ets>, Icel. <ets>sko<?/a</ets>, Goth.
us<ets>skawjan</ets> to waken, <ets>skuggwa</ets> a mirror, Icel.
<ets>skuggy</ets> shade, shadow, L. <ets>cavere</ets> to be on one's
guard, Gr. <?/<?/<?/ to mark, perceive, hear, Skr. <ets>kavi</ets> wise.
Cf. <er>Caution</er>, <er>Scavenger</er>, <er>Sheen</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To exhibit or present to view; to place in sight; to
display; -- the thing exhibited being the object, and often with an
indirect object denoting the person or thing seeing or beholding;
<as>as, to <ex>show</ex> a house; <ex>show</ex> your colors; shopkeepers
<ex>show</ex> customers goods (show goods to customers).</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Go thy way, <qex>shew</qex> thyself to the priest.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. viii. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor want we skill or art from whence to raise⟦br⟧
Magnificence; and what can heaven <qex>show</qex> more?</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To exhibit to the mental view; to tell; to disclose;
to reveal; to make known; <as>as, to <ex>show</ex> one's
designs</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Shew</qex> them the way wherein they must walk.</q>
<rj><qau>Ex. xviii. 20.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If it please my father to do thee evil, then I will
<qex>shew</qex> it thee, and send thee away.</q> <rj><qau>1 Sam. xx.
13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Specifically, to make known the way to (a person);
hence, to direct; to guide; to usher; to conduct; <as>as, to
<ex>show</ex> a person into a parlor; to <ex>show</ex> one to the
door</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make apparent or clear, as by evidence,
testimony, or reasoning; to prove; to explain; also, to manifest; to
evince; <as>as, to <ex>show</ex> the truth of a statement; to
<ex>show</ex> the causes of an event</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I 'll <qex>show</qex> my duty by my timely care.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To bestow; to confer; to afford; <as>as, to
<ex>show</ex> favor</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Shewing</qex> mercy unto thousands of them that love me.</q>
<rj><qau>Ex. xx. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To show forth</b></col>, <cd>to manifest; to publish; to
proclaim.</cd> -- <col><b>To show his paces</b></col>, <cd>to exhibit
the gait, speed, or the like; -- said especially of a horse.</cd> --
<col><b>To show off</b></col>, <cd>to exhibit ostentatiously.</cd> --
<col><b>To show up</b></col>, <cd>to expose.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Show</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Show
<hw>Show</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Written also
<ets>shew</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To exhibit or manifest one's
self or itself; to appear; to look; to be in appearance; to
seem.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Just such she <qex>shows</qex> before a rising storm.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All round a hedge upshoots, and <qex>shows</qex>⟦br⟧
At distance like a little wood.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1334 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To have a certain appearance, as well or ill, fit or
unfit; to become or suit; to appear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My lord of York, it better <qex>showed</qex> with you.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To show off</b></col>, <cd>to make a show; to display
one's self.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Show</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Show
<hw>Show</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Formerly written also
<ets>shew</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of showing, or bringing
to view; exposure to sight; exhibition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is shown, or brought to view; that which
is arranged to be seen; a spectacle; an exhibition; <as>as, a traveling
<ex>show</ex>; a cattle <ex>show</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As for triumphs, masks, feasts, and such <qex>shows</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Proud or ostentatious display; parade;
pomp.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I envy none their pageantry and <qex>show</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Semblance; likeness; appearance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He through the midst unmarked,⟦br⟧
In <qex>show</qex> plebeian angel militant⟦br⟧
Of lowest order, passed.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>False semblance; deceitful appearance;
pretense.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Beware of the scribes, . . . which devour widows' houses, and for
a <qex>shew</qex> make long prayers.</q> <rj><qau>Luke xx. 46.
47.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A discharge, from the vagina, of
mucus streaked with blood, occurring a short time before
labor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A pale blue flame, at the top of
a candle flame, indicating the presence of fire damp.</def>
<rj><au>Raymond.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Show bill</b></col>, <cd>a broad sheet containing an
advertisement in large letters.</cd> -- <col><b>Show box</b></col>,
<cd>a box containing some object of curiosity carried round as a
show.</cd> -- <col><b>Show card</b></col>, <cd>an advertising placard;
also, a card for displaying samples.</cd> -- <col><b>Show
case</b></col>, <cd>a glazed case, box, or cabinet for displaying and
protecting shopkeepers' wares, articles on exhibition in museums,
etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Show glass</b></col>, <cd>a glass which displays
objects; a mirror.</cd> -- <col><b>Show of hands</b></col>, <cd>a
raising of hands to indicate judgment; as, the vote was taken by a
<xex>show of hands</xex>.</cd> -- <col><b>Show stone</b></col>, <cd>a
piece of glass or crystal supposed to have the property of exhibiting
images of persons or things not present, indicating in that way future
events.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Showbread</ent>⟦br⟧
